### **Classroom Material: Student Handout**

**Course:** EE 301 - Power Systems I
**Topic:** Introduction & Basic Structure

**Definitions to Remember:**
| Term | Definition | Typical Voltage |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Generation** | Conversion of primary energy to electricity. | 11 kV - 25 kV |
| **Step-up Transformer** | Increases voltage for transmission to reduce $I^2R$ losses. | Low $\rightarrow$ High |
| **Transmission** | Bulk transfer of power over long distances. | 110 kV - 765 kV |
| **Distribution** | Final delivery to end-users. | 400V - 33 kV |
| **Busbar** | A connection point (node) for lines and equipment. | N/A |

**Discussion Question for Next Class:**
If we increase the transmission voltage, we reduce line losses. So, why don't we just transmit at 10 million volts? What is the limiting factor? (Hint: Think about what happens to air when electrical pressure gets too high).

